			<tr>
				<td colspan="2" height="100%" valign="top"><span class="postbody">Excellent examination of the problem of paying to raid.
<br />

<br />
Do you think that this was an intentionally large burden on raid forces? I think perhaps that Blizzard designers were probably sitting around a table and said, "Ok, repair costs are very manageable for single players who are leveling or grinding, but they're not an adequate money sink. We're going to have to create a larger sink somewhere else. Maybe we should take it out of raider's pockets since they're the "wealthiest" players in the game?"
<br />

<br />
One possible fix: Increase the flow of coin drops from raid zones like UBRS and MC. Why not have each member of the raid party walk out 4 gold richer at the end of one of these raids? The problem is, how do you counter this increased faucet? Perhaps with a zone entry fee of some sort (require the RAID LEADER to purchase "attunement shards" or somesuch from a vendor near the zone line). That would effectively transfer the cost of raiding from the individual to the guild bank.
<br />

<br />
What's really problematic here are the set prices for commodity goods. <B>MMO designers have it all wrong</B>. In an MMO where you can sell drops to vendors for gold, you essentially have an ever-expanding money supply. 
<br />

<br />
<b>per-capita income</b>
<br />
Let's say that the average player on a server earns 20 gold per week, or 1040 gold per year in the course of normal activities. Some players of course will earn this much in a week. And some will run negative balances and will borrow from more wealthy friends. If you've got an average per-capita income of 520 gold per year and a server has 3000 players, you've got a "money supply" that increases by 3.1 million gold per year. You can either design more money sinks to try to soak up some of this money, or you can tighten money supply. If you don't do anything about it, you've essentially got run-away inflation.
<br />

<br />
<b>stopping ever-expanding money supply and the inflation that it causes</b>
<br />

<br />
The ideal way to stop ever-expanding money supply and to curb inflation is to get rid of fixed vendor prices. In the real world, prices are seldom fixed. If a gallon of milk costs $2.00 this year, it will probably cost $2.04 next year. Prices for goods respond to the cost to produce those goods.
<br />

<br />
Similarly, MMO designers should set up an "inflation multiplier" for all vendor goods. If a gallon of milk at a vendor costs $.20 when the game is launched (when money supply is essentially zero), then the price of this milk should change in accordance with how much money is floating around in the economy. Of course, if milk increases from $.20 per gallon to $2.00 per gallon, game citizens will complain as loudly as real-life citizens do when faced with inflation that erodes the value of their income-generating activities.
<br />

<br />
That's where the next fundamental change comes in: CONTROL money supply by dynamically changing all cash drops. Let's say a world Zombie has $.40 in his pocket when he's killed. That number should fall when money is plentiful. That number should rise when money is scarce.
<br />

<br />
Essentially, what the "government" of the game should look to do is exercise the same controls over money supply that any central bank exercises. It should seek to keep money supply relatively constant (or growing at a controlled rate). It can do this by dynamically changing the value of vendor goods and incomes. 
<br />

<br />
A mechanism like this will keep quests from being devalued. (Quests should also be dynamically adjusted for inflation. If a quest yields $3.00 at launch, it should yield significantly more in a world with much more money floating about it.) 
<br />

<br />
Most mainstream MMOs don't try to simulate dynamic economies, mostly because players don't really understand what they're missing. You can't put "dynamically controlled money supply!" on the box at the store. No game player would really care, much less understand. This sort of economic architecture will only prove its value once the game's been around for a few years and players begin to notice that the typical hyper-inflation that plagues games of this genre doesn't exist.
<br />

<br />
<b>summary</b>
<br />

<br />
1. <b>FAUCETS</b>: Cash and cash equivalents dropped from monsters should vary in order to keep money supply in check. Money supply must not be allowed to grow and grow.
<br />

<br />
2. <b>SINKS</b>: The prices of common goods required for player upkeep (repairs, food, water, tradeskill items) should rise or fall in accordance with available money supply. If money is plentiful, players should be willing to pay more for basic goods. Your parents or grandparents paid $.25 for a gallon of milk, but their incomes were tiny compared to your income. You are willing to pay $2.50 for a gallon of milk precisely because you have more money.
<br />

<br />
3. <b>HIRE AN ECONOMIST</B>: This sort of system can be handled programmatically, but you're going to need a good economist to help you set it up and to help you define and measure the game economy in a way that makes sense. You'll need to define an in-game CPI, in-game GDP, and in-game per capita income. Otherwise, your system will suck. ;)
<br />

<br />
This is just top-of-the-mind ramblings. There's so much more to modeling a good system, but luckily these are pretty simple economies. It's not that hard.</span><br /><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
