			<tr>
				<td colspan="2" height="100%" valign="top"><span class="postbody">There are a few games that focused on econmy quite a bit. Ultima Online and Shadowbane were the ones I played extensively. This was addressed extensivly by Shadowbane developers. They went even further to describe different economic transactions, net loss, net gain and net zero. When you take 100g out of your pocket to buy a weapon at the AH, neither the money nor the item is removed from the world economy, so buying upgrades from other players is a net zero transaction to the world economy. Selling that item when you get an upgrade is also net zero, because the game gives you the item value. WoW did an Excellent job by creating bind on equip items of preventing Item Inflation. If only 1 person can ever use the item, there can be no hand me downs. So Kudos on removing items from the economy, good drain there. The problem with a stable game economy is it REQUIRES that you lose as much money as you make. people play the game to have fun, and losing as much as you make is not fun.
<br />

<br />
The majority of transactions in this and most games is income (kill monster get stuff) or net zero (sell stuff for cash, or to other players). The net drain is repairing durability, regent costs, a small AH fee, Postage, transportation (including mounts) , but these costs dont compare to the income.
<br />

<br />
The problem I see with game economys is the horde and wait mentality. you save up gold for the item you want, keeping the gold in the economy. With your solution of controlled income, I could see this problem being even worse. You are right it would lower the prices on items, but it would reward the people most responsible for hording liquid assets, and affect people just starting the same way inflation would.
<br />

<br />
The problem lies in creating a net drain transaction that ganks a ton of peoples hard earned cash, but is somehow fun. In the history of video games it has not been done. If I were to take a swing at it, it would probably be something like a lottery/casino. As a game master you would have great control on the payout ratio, and it neednt be great. a 1g lottery ticket, people buy 3k, and the winner gets 1k.... the winner is happy, and you drained 2k out of the economy. Voluntary basis makes it not burdensome, like the chore of repairing.
<br />

<br />
As far as this specific problem... I dont think its gonna change any time soon. It does seem like a rich tax, but the game needs drains somewhere.  I would be surprised if the guildbank foots the bill. Someone needs to pay, but the membership of the guild IS the guild, so I think that individuals paying for themselves is fair.</span><br /><span class="gensmall"></span></td>
			</tr>
